Several opposition parties, particularly the DA, have reiterated soldiers&#8217; deployment during Sona exceeded a mere ceremonial role. CAPE TOWN Defence Minister Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula says a full report on soldiers deployed during this year s State of the Nation Address (Sona) will be given to Parliament s presiding officers soon.National Assembly Speaker Baleka Mbete had requested clarity following an outcry from some opposition parties over the extent of the South African National Defence Force (SANDF) s presence during Sona last month. The Democratic Alliance (DA) has filed an application at the Western Cape High Court, seeking a declaration that soldier deployment in the parliamentary precinct for non-ceremonial purposes is unconstitutional and unlawful.Several opposition parties, particularly the DA, have reiterated soldiers deployment during Sona exceeded a mere ceremonial role.Mapisa-Nqakula has given the assurance full details around SANDF s presence will be provided. If you allow me, rather we give that answer through the presiding officers of Parliament, so that through Parliament we can then respond to the questions raised by South Africans. Prior to the Sona on 9 February, the Presidency communicated that 441 soldiers would be deployed from 5 to 10 February.[WATCH FROM THE ARCHIVE] Is this why Sona security was heightened?